<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1901-12-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1901-12-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="79" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d79">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Wu</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901-12-03"><hi rend="italic">December 3,
                                1901</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 187.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of your note No. 214, of the 28th ultimo, requesting that
                            permission be granted to the Chinese student, Tong Tseng, whose case is
                            described in your note, to land at Honolulu, to which place he goes for
                            the purpose of pursuing an educational course.</p>
                        <p>In reply I have the honor to inform you that I have sent a copy of your
                            note to the Secretary of the Treasury for his information, and have
                            commended the case to his consideration.</p>
                        <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>